R Plot Collection Part 1.

a brief of visualization using the German Mortality Data 2023

About This Document

This is my personal collection of R plotting code, using the German Mortality Data 2023 dataset as practice material. Part 1 focuses on commonly used graph types that I frequently see in scientific articles and publications - basic distributions, geographic visualizations, and comparative plots. This is purely for coding reference and learning different visualization techniques, not for scientific analysis.

How to read this document - When code is hidden (echo=FALSE), treat the output as data visualization and descriptive insight. - When code is shown (echo=TRUE), treat the section as part of a code example library you can reuse.

1. General Analysis

Distribution Patterns Using Scatter, Heatmap, and Trend Visualizations

This section presents an overview of mortality patterns across Germany in 2023, examining relationships between causes of death, age groups, and sex through multiple visualization techniques including scatter plots, heatmaps, point plots, and boxplots.

1.1 Scatter Plot: Sex-based Distribution of Deaths by ICD Categories

Logarithmic scatter plot comparing mortality counts across ICD-10 classification categories, faceted by sex

#Scatter plot von value Distribution of type, facetting by sex
plotluck(csv23212s, W.mi~Merkmal_1 | Geschlecht, opts = plotluck.options(trans.log.thresh =10)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "right") + 
  labs(
    title = "Scatter plot of deaths by selected causes and sex, Germany, 2023",
    y = "Count,per 100,000 inhabitants",
    x = "ICD",
    color = "Sex"
  )

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

In this figure, death counts are plotted across ICD-10 chapters as a horizontal scatter and the panels are split by sex. The horizontal axis shows the value (count per 100,000 inhabitants) and is displayed on a logarithmic scale above 10, and the vertical axis lists the ICD-10 chapters. Each point denotes one age group within its chapter, although age is not mapped to an axis. The spread of points within a chapter summarizes how age-specific counts are distributed for that cause category, and the side by side panels allow a direct comparison of these distributions between male and female.

Description

This horizontal dot plot summarizes, for each ICD-10 chapter, the spread of age-specific counts along the count axis. Tight clusters indicate similar counts across age groups; wider clusters indicate greater between-age variability. Right-shifted clusters correspond to higher overall counts. Colors distinguish male and female distributions within the same ICD-10. Because age is not on an axis, the figure characterizes within-ICD distributions rather than age-specific peaks.

In this figure, P00–P96 shows the lowest overall counts, with the female cluster slightly further left than the male; I00–I99 exhibits a broadly even spread and the highest maximum among chapters, with a somewhat wider range for females; C00–D48 is similar to I00–I99 with the second-highest maximum, but here the male distribution spans a wider range than the female.

1.2 Heatmap: Age-stratified Mortality Patterns by Cause and Sex

Logarithmically scaled heatmap displaying mortality intensity across age groups, ICD categories, and sex with gradient coloring

#resharp of table csv23212s
strbkata <- tibble(
  'typ' = csv23212s$Merkmal_1,
  'age' = csv23212s$Merkmal_3,
  'sex' = csv23212s$Geschlecht,
  fill = csv23212s$Wert)

strbkata_clean <- strbkata %>% na.omit()
ggplot(strbkata_clean, aes(x = age, y = typ, fill = fill)) +
  geom_tile(color = "#ffffff") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(
    low = "#317479",
    mid = "#d0d7e8",
    high = "#e57259",
    midpoint = median(log10(strbkata$fill), na.rm = TRUE),
    trans = "log10",
    name = "Count",
    breaks = c(1, 10, 100, 1000, 1000, 10000),
    labels = scales::label_log()
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex) +
  labs(
    title = "Heatmap of deaths by selected causes, age group, and sex, Germany, 2023",
    x = "Age",
    y = "ICD"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(family = "Arial", size = 14, hjust = 0.5, vjust = 0.5),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "right")

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

In this figure, the horizontal axis lists age groups and the vertical axis lists ICD-10 chapters; each tile represents one age-by-ICD combination, and the fill encodes the death count. Using a teal-to-coral gradient on a log scale allows single-digit and very large values to be read on the same map. Faceting by sex places the panels side by side, providing a comprehensive view of age patterns and sex differences without displaying within-category spans explicitly. Compared with the dot plot in 1.1, this heatmap does not display the span of within-category values, but it does convey the magnitude of counts and the age-related structure of those magnitudes.

Description

In this figure, the heatmap summarizes, for each sex, how counts distribute across the joint space of age and ICD-10 chapter. Age groups are ordered from youngest to oldest, so left-to-right color changes indicate age-dependent change. ICD-10 chapters are categorical and appear in their standard alphanumeric order.

P00–P96 and Q00–Q99 are brightest at the youngest ages. Most ICD-10 chapters show increasing intensity with age; this trend is most pronounced for I00–I99 and C00–D48, which are brightest at older ages and already begin to intensify from the 30–40 age range. The side-by-side panels make sex differences visible. In V01–Y98, the rise in intensity begins at younger ages for males than for females.

1.3 Point Plot: Age Progression Trends for Each Cause of Death

Multi-panel point plot with logarithmic y-axis showing age-related mortality trends, color-coded by sex

strbkata_clean <- strbkata_clean %>%
  mutate(age = factor(age, levels = unique(age)))

ggplot(strbkata_clean, aes(x = age, y = fill)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = sex),size = 0.8) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("male" = "#d78a6d", "female" = "#adc9c9")) +
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(
    title = "Trend of death counts by age, sex, and cause of death, Germany, 2023",
    x = "Age",
    y = "Count",
    color = "Sex"
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ typ)+
  theme_classic() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size = 6.5),
    legend.position = "right"
  )

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

This figure plots age-specific death counts with age on the horizontal axis and count on the vertical axis, which is shown on a base-10 logarithmic scale. Points are coloured by sex and panels are faceted by ICD-10 chapter. The left-to-right pattern within each panel shows how counts change across ordered age groups for that chapter. Colour by sex highlights differences in level and trajectory; these visual differences can be formally evaluated with statistical tests, for example age-by-sex interaction models or paired comparisons within age groups, to assess whether they are present and how large they are.

Description

Each panel corresponds to one ICD-10 chapter and shows the age profile of death counts for males and females. Age groups progress from the youngest to the oldest along the horizontal axis; vertical separation at a given age indicates a sex difference in level. The logarithmic vertical scale places early-life and late-life counts in the same view and makes monotonic increases or early upturns easier to read.

P00–P96 and Q00–Q99 show a pronounced peak at the earliest ages, followed by a rapid decline that settles into a relatively stable level. By contrast, I00–I99, J00–J99, and E00–E90 dip in early life and then rise steadily with advancing age. C00–D48 and K00–K93 trace a subtle S-shaped course, with a midlife inflection before leveling at older ages. In V01–Y98, sex differences are more evident, as the male trajectory turns upward earlier than the female.

1.4 Boxplot: Statistical Distribution of Mortality Counts by Cause

Logarithmic boxplot comparing death count distributions across ICD categories, stratified by sex with outlier visualization

ggplot(strbkata_clean, aes(x = typ, y = fill, fill = sex)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = sex), 
               outlier.colour = "#838d93", 
               outlier.shape = 16,       
               outlier.size = 1,        
               notch = FALSE,            
               notchwidth = 0.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("male" = "#d78a6d", "female" = "#adc9c9")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("male" = "#e89b7e", "female" = "#bedada")) + 
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(
    title = "Boxplot of death counts by cause and sex of death, Germany, 2023",
    x = "ICD",
    y = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "right"
  )

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

This figure summarizes death counts by ICD-10 chapter and sex using boxplots. The horizontal axis lists ICD-10 chapters and the vertical axis shows Count on a base-10 logarithmic scale. For each chapter, one box per sex aggregates the age-group counts: the line marks the median, the box spans the interquartile range, the whiskers show the non-outlying range, and points indicate outlying age groups.

Description

Read each chapter vertically to compare the typical level and variability across ages for males and females. Higher medians indicate higher typical counts; wider boxes or longer whiskers indicate greater between-age dispersion; numerous outliers mark age groups that deviate strongly from the chapter’s bulk. Vertical separation between the two boxes within a chapter reflects sex differences at the chapter level.

Across chapters, I00–I99 and C00–D48 show the highest medians with wide IQRs; males are higher and more dispersed than females. J00–J99 and K00–K93 sit at a mid-to-high level with noticeable spread, while E00–E90 and G00–G99 are intermediate with moderate dispersion. At the low end, P00–P96 and Q00–Q99 have very low medians and narrow boxes. V01–Y98 shows a clear sex contrast with a higher and wider male distribution. Because the y-axis is logarithmic, equal vertical gaps indicate multiplicative differences; non-overlapping boxes imply a marked sex difference in typical level.

2. Geographic Analysis

Regional Distribution Using Choropleth Map and State-level Heatmap

This section examines spatial patterns of mortality across German federal states, utilizing geographic visualizations to identify regional variations in specific causes of death and overall mortality patterns through maps and heatmaps.

library(sf)
library(rnaturalearth)
library(rnaturalearthdata)
# data import
deu23 <- read_excel('statistischer-bericht-todesursachen-2120400237005.xlsx', sheet = 'csv-23211-05')
deu23mi <- read_excel('statistischer-bericht-todesursachen-2120400237005.xlsx', sheet = 'csv-23211-06')

deu23$Gebiet <- as.factor(deu23$Gebiet)
deu23$Merkmal_1 <- as.factor(deu23$Merkmal_1)
deu23$Wert <- as.numeric(deu23$Wert)
deu23$W.mi <- as.numeric(deu23mi$Wert)
deu23 <- deu23 %>% filter(Merkmal_1 != 'A00-U85')

deu23oh <- subset(deu23, subset = Merkmal_1 == 'V01-V99' & Gebiet != "Deutschland")
c00 <- data.frame(Region = deu23oh$Gebiet, Anzahl = deu23oh$W.mi)

germany_map <- ne_states(country = "Germany", returnclass = "sf")
germany_map <- germany_map %>%
  dplyr::rename(Region = name)

merged_data <- dplyr::left_join(germany_map, c00, by = "Region")

2.1 Choropleth Map: Traffic Accident Mortality Rates Across German States

Gradient-filled geographic map displaying mortality rates per 100,000 inhabitants from transport accidents (ICD V01-V99)

# Plot
ggplot(data = merged_data) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Anzahl), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "Anzahl", limits = c(min(c00$Anzahl), max(c00$Anzahl))) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Map of mortality rates (per 100,000 inhabitants) from V01–V99, 2023", fill = "rate") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")+
  scale_fill_gradient(low = '#ffffff', high = '#55aacc')+
  theme(
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    plot.margin = margin(0, 0, 0, 0),
    plot.title = element_text(family = "Arial", size = 14, hjust = 0.5, vjust = 0.5)
  )

Example1: C00-D48 Example2: F00-F99

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

These figures are choropleths that shade German federal states to encode mortality rates per 100,000 inhabitants for a given ICD-10 chapter. There are no numeric axes because position is geographic. Each polygon is one state; the fill colour maps the rate on a continuous legend so that darker shades indicate higher mortality and lighter shades indicate lower values. Read them by comparing colour intensity across states and consulting the legend for approximate numeric rates.


Description

These three choropleths map mortality rates per 100,000 inhabitants by German federal state for transport accidents (V01–V99, blue), neoplasms (C00–D48, grey), and mental and behavioural disorders (F00–F99, pink). Each polygon represents one state; colour intensity is read against a continuous legend, with darker shades indicating higher rates and lighter shades lower rates, enabling state-to-state comparison on a population-standardised basis. In the blue transport-accident map (V01–V99), darker tones form a corridor across the central to mid-western states, while the north-eastern region is noticeably lighter, indicating comparatively lower rates; several other states fall between these extremes. In the grey neoplasm map (C00–D48), shading is fairly uniform overall, but parts of the central and western states show somewhat darker fills than their neighbours, suggesting modestly higher rates there. In the pink mental/behavioural map (F00–F99), the central to north-western band is predominantly darker, and Saxony in the east also stands out as darker than adjacent states; other regions tend to sit closer to the middle of the legend’s range. All three figures summarise differences at the state level; they do not display within-state variation or finer local patterns.

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

A state-by-cause heatmap that shades German federal states in rows against ICD-10 chapters in columns. Each tile represents one state × ICD combination and the fill encodes the number of deaths on a continuous light-to-dark scale (darker = more deaths). Axes are categorical: ICD-10 chapters are shown in their standard alphanumeric order along the x-axis; state names appear on the y-axis. Grey tiles denote missing or not-applicable values for the corresponding cell. This display is useful for scanning which causes contribute the largest absolute death counts in each state and for comparing column-wise or row-wise patterns at a glance.

Description

Counts concentrate in a few columns across most states: I00–I99 and C00–D48 show the darkest bands, indicating the largest absolute contributions to mortality. Large, populous states such as Nordrhein-Westfalen and Bayern display darker tiles across several causes, whereas smaller states (for example Bremen, Saarland) are lighter overall. The column O00–O99 appears greyed, reflecting missing or not-applicable entries in this extract. Because the metric is absolute counts, the heatmap reflects population size as well as cause structure; for risk comparison across states, a rate-based version (per 100,000) would be more appropriate.

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

This figure displays mortality rates per 100,000 inhabitants by selected causes of death in Berlin, 2023, with comparison to Germany. The vertical axis shows the mortality rate on a log10 scale, and the horizontal axis lists specific ICD-10 codes. Bars are colored by ICD-10 chapter category, with Berlin rates shown as colored bars and Germany rates indicated by black dots for comparison.

Description

The figure reveals substantial variation in mortality rates spanning several orders of magnitude. Circulatory System diseases (green bars, especially I25, I50, I21) demonstrate the highest mortality rates, with I25 exceeding 100 per 100,000. Neoplasms (orange bars, particularly C34, C25, C61-C67) show rates ranging from approximately 1 to 100 per 100,000. Respiratory diseases (teal bars, J18, J44) display rates around 10-100 or more per 100,000. In contrast, Perinatal Conditions (purple) and certain External Causes (pink, right side) show the lowest rates, ranging from 0.1 to 10 per 100,000, representing differences of 1-3 orders of magnitude compared to the leading causes.

Berlin’s rates generally align closely with German national averages across most categories, though minor deviations appear in specific causes within External Causes and Symptoms & Signs categories.

3.2 Donut Chart: Proportional Distribution of Leading Causes in Berlin

Polar coordinate donut chart showing proportional breakdown of the top 12 causes of death, with radial labels displaying counts and percentages

filtered_dataoh2ber <- filtered_dataoh %>% filter(Gebiet == 'Berlin')
ber23dfw <- data.frame(Typ = filtered_dataoh2ber$ICD, Anzahl = filtered_dataoh2ber$Wert)
ber23dffwnr <- ber23dfw[!is.na(ber23dfw$Anzahl),]
ber23dffwnr$pre <- ber23dffwnr$Anzahl /sum(ber23dffwnr$Anzahl)

#cumulative percentages (top of each rectangle)
ber23dffwnr$ymax <- cumsum(ber23dffwnr$pre)
#bottom of each rectangle
ber23dffwnr$ymin <- c(0, head(ber23dffwnr$ymax, n=-1))

#label position
ber23dffwnr$labelPosition <- (ber23dffwnr$ymax + ber23dffwnr$ymin) / 2
#label text
ber23dffwnr$label <- paste0("\n number: ", ber23dffwnr$Anzahl,"\n rate: ",100*round(ber23dffwnr$pre,2),'%')

ber23dffwnr <- ber23dffwnr %>%
  mutate(
    mid = (ymax + ymin) / 2,                 
    angle = 90 - 360 * mid / max(ymax),      
    hjust = ifelse(angle < -90, 1, 0),       
    angle = ifelse(angle < -90, angle + 180, angle) 
  )

ggplot(ber23dffwnr, aes(ymax=ymax, ymin=ymin, xmax=5, xmin=2.5, fill=Typ)) +
  geom_rect() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette='Set3') +
  geom_segment(
    data = ber23dffwnr %>%
      dplyr::arrange(desc(pre)) %>%
      dplyr::slice_head(n = 12),
    aes(x = 5, xend = 5.4, y = mid, yend = mid),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    color = "grey50"
  ) +
  geom_text(
    data = ber23dffwnr %>%
      dplyr::arrange(desc(pre)) %>%  
      dplyr::slice_head(n = 12),       
    aes(x = 5.5, y = mid, label = label, hjust = hjust,angle = angle),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    size = 3
  )+

Source: Destatis, Todesursachen 2023

This donut chart displays the proportion of selected causes of death in Berlin, 2023, by ICD-10 chapter. Donut charts show part-to-whole relationships through circular segments, where arc length represents each category’s proportion of the total. Each segment is labeled with the ICD-10 code range, absolute count, and percentage.

Description

Three major categories dominate Berlin mortality: Circulatory diseases (I00-I99, orange) represent the largest share at 32% (11,770 deaths), followed by neoplasms (C00-D48, teal) at 26% (9,418 deaths), and respiratory diseases (J00-J99, lime green) at 8% (3,050 deaths). Together, these account for approximately two-thirds of all deaths. Mid-sized segments include mental disorders (F00-F99, 7%), digestive diseases (K00-K93, 6%), endocrine/metabolic diseases (E00-E90, 4%), and external causes (V01-Y98, 4%). The smallest segments represent genitourinary (3%), symptoms/signs (3%), blood disorders (2%), musculoskeletal diseases (1%), and nervous system diseases (<1%).

Reference
